description.plain:
Three 6 Mafia, originally known as Backyard Posse and Triple 6 Mafia, is an incredibly influential hardcore rap group from Memphis, Tennessee. Started in 1991 by Juicy J, D.J. Paul, and Lord Infamous—who died in 2013—Crunchy Black, Gangsta Boo, and Koopsta Knicca have all been part of the Mafia.



Mystic Stylez, their 1995 debut album, inspired a lo-fi Horrorcore movement in the 2010’s; SpaceGhostPurrp, Denzel Curry, $UICIDEBOY$, A$AP Rocky and Lil Ugly Mane all were influenced by Mystic Stylez dark sound.

The Mafia is also known for coining the term “crunk,” a style of music famous for heavy basslines and shouted vocals.

“It’s Hard Out Here For a Pimp,” off the soundtrack to Hustle & Flow, won best original song at the Academy Awards in 2005.

The Three 6 Mafia is responsible for kick starting the careers of Frayser Boy, Gangsta Blac, Lil Wyte, Indo G, T. Rock, Playa Fly, Killa Klan Kaze, La Chat, and Al Kapone. The group frequently collaborates with Project Pat.

description.plain:
Sampling a classic Marvin Gaye song – “Is That Enough?” – “Sippin' on Some Syrup” represents the hardcore partying lifestyle of southern trap-rappers. The eponymous ‘syrup’ refers to a mixture of Codeine/Promethazine prescription cough medicine and soda, which when mixed creates lean, a classic southern concoction and tradition.

“Sippin' on Some Syrup” charted on the US Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs (Billboard) at #30.

description.plain:
Widely considered a southern hip-hop classic, “Stay Fly” is a triumphant and unforgiving trunk-rattler anthem straight out of Memphis, Tennessee. Released as the first single from dirty south pioneers Three 6 Mafia’s 2006 hit album Most Known Unknown, the song features fellow Memphis natives 8Ball & MJG and Young Buck. “Stay Fly” became Three 6 Mafia’s biggest song ever, peaking at #13 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart and becoming certified 2x platinum by the RIAA on December 11, 2006.

“Stay Fly” has stirred up some controversy over the years because of its perceived demonic messages. It is a theory among some fans that the background vocals, taken from “Tell Me Why Our Love Has Turned Cold” by Willie Hutch, were altered to say “Lucifer, you’re my king, you’re my father.” The rap group has long been associated with Satan and took their name directly from 666, the “Number of the Beast.”

A music video for “Stay Fly” was also released to support the single. It was later remixed with guest verses from southern rappers Trick Daddy, Slim Thug, and Three 6 Mafia affiliate Project Pat as “Stay Fly (Still Fly Remix).”

description.plain:
Poppin' My Collar is the second single from Most Known Unknown. The song was very well received, peaking at #21 on the Billboard Hot 100, making it the group’s second Top 40 hit.

The track is an anthem for the style of “popping” the collar of a shirt (allowing the collar to stay upright instead of folding it), a trend that rose with the preppy movement’s return in around 2005.

A quintessential Three 6 song, Break Da Law ‘95 is one of the biggest early Mafia hits, featuring DJ Paul on the verses and samples of Playa Fly and Skinny Pimp on the hook.

The instrumental also contains samples from a variety of tracks, including the legendary Memphis track “2 Thick” by DJ Zirk, “Play This Only at Night” by Doug E. Fresh and the soundtrack from Wes Craven’s New Nightmare.

description.plain:
With an introduction sampling the 1995 horror movie Brain Scan and harboring a similar sentiment in its lyrical expression; Fuckin' Wit Dis Click is the six-minute horrorcore cornerstone of Three 6 Mafia’s debut LP.

Featuring a notably macabre verse from DJ Paul and Lord Infamous' innovative use of a triplet flow; this track demonstrated Three 6 were to be taken seriously.
